1
00:00:04,304 --> 00:00:06,426
So we all wear a lot of hats, right?

2
00:00:06,826 --> 00:00:08,247
That's a thing that we say.

3
00:00:08,267 --> 00:00:10,308
If you're an independent game developer,

4
00:00:10,388 --> 00:00:12,950
I feel like you're contractually obligated

5
00:00:12,990 --> 00:00:14,451
to say it at least once.

6
00:00:15,252 --> 00:00:17,413
It is a truism in indie games, we have less,

7
00:00:17,934 --> 00:00:21,376
so we need to do more, we wear a lot of hats.

8
00:00:21,396 --> 00:00:24,578
I have worn a lot of hats, and they got heavy,

9
00:00:25,339 --> 00:00:26,700
and they hurt quite a bit.

10
00:00:28,213 --> 00:00:29,554
That's how I like to introduce myself.

11
00:00:29,814 --> 00:00:30,835
My name is John Remedios.

12
00:00:31,055 --> 00:00:33,137
I'm a game designer and developer from Toronto, Canada.

13
00:00:33,277 --> 00:00:36,259
I've been working in video games for just over nine years.

14
00:00:36,640 --> 00:00:39,462
I went independent in 2015 when I found in my studio

15
00:00:40,063 --> 00:00:40,823
Actual Humans.

16
00:00:41,604 --> 00:00:44,066
The first game from Actual Humans

17
00:00:44,326 --> 00:00:45,387
is called Shoot Shoot Megapack.

18
00:00:45,467 --> 00:00:47,569
It is a modular, minimalist party game

19
00:00:47,669 --> 00:00:49,630
about rules, friendship, and shooting.

20
00:00:50,171 --> 00:00:52,293
Like I said, it is the only commercial game

21
00:00:52,353 --> 00:00:55,335
I've released independently, so surprise, surprise,

22
00:00:55,355 --> 00:00:57,797
I goofed up a whole bunch.

23
00:00:59,522 --> 00:01:00,743
It went way over schedule.

24
00:01:00,903 --> 00:01:02,904
It did not hit its sales targets.

25
00:01:03,465 --> 00:01:05,066
It's not on all the platforms it should be.

26
00:01:05,266 --> 00:01:08,208
The name is a bit of a hard sell,

27
00:01:08,948 --> 00:01:11,430
and it doesn't stand out.

28
00:01:14,652 --> 00:01:16,953
However, it did have its fair share of successes.

29
00:01:16,973 --> 00:01:18,994
It's a good animation.

30
00:01:19,014 --> 00:01:22,416
It met its design goals,

31
00:01:22,536 --> 00:01:25,698
like literally every single one that I set out to hit.

32
00:01:26,579 --> 00:01:27,740
I built a number of

33
00:01:28,193 --> 00:01:32,916
professional and personal relationships because of this game, and I think it looks and feels

34
00:01:32,976 --> 00:01:33,417
quite nice.

35
00:01:34,157 --> 00:01:37,420
But most importantly to me, it found its audience.

36
00:01:38,280 --> 00:01:39,481
So these are teens.

37
00:01:42,103 --> 00:01:43,765
In case you are unfamiliar.

38
00:01:45,246 --> 00:01:50,650
When I showed SSMP for the first time publicly in the Megabooth at PAX Prime 2015, before

39
00:01:50,690 --> 00:01:56,754
it was even PAX West, these three fine folks came and played the demo literally every single

40
00:01:56,774 --> 00:01:57,755
day at least once.

41
00:01:58,885 --> 00:02:01,628
And then they did it again when I showed in 2016.

42
00:02:01,988 --> 00:02:06,272
And when the game was in the PAX 10 in 2017,

43
00:02:06,412 --> 00:02:07,873
even though we had already released.

44
00:02:09,354 --> 00:02:11,116
In 2018, I was just at PAX hanging out,

45
00:02:11,236 --> 00:02:13,398
and so we became buds.

46
00:02:16,401 --> 00:02:19,723
When I launched SSMP, they bought the game day one,

47
00:02:20,064 --> 00:02:22,346
put it on a laptop, and brought it to school,

48
00:02:22,646 --> 00:02:24,007
and played it with their friends over lunch.

49
00:02:24,347 --> 00:02:24,987
throughout the school year.

50
00:02:25,007 --> 00:02:25,868
They're all in college now.

51
00:02:25,968 --> 00:02:27,429
I don't know if they're still gonna do this

52
00:02:27,509 --> 00:02:28,830
with their fun college friends.

53
00:02:30,111 --> 00:02:32,273
Hopefully they will, but in my mind,

54
00:02:32,493 --> 00:02:34,634
this is what success looks like.

55
00:02:35,815 --> 00:02:39,898
However, the way I made SMP is not a story of success.

56
00:02:42,300 --> 00:02:43,521
The game was not built sustainably,

57
00:02:43,781 --> 00:02:46,483
and by that I mean the mental and emotional costs

58
00:02:46,683 --> 00:02:48,104
of its development would not have been worth it,

59
00:02:48,305 --> 00:02:51,687
even if it had been some raging commercial success.

60
00:02:52,208 --> 00:02:53,248
Realistically, I could.

61
00:02:53,985 --> 00:02:57,408
make one, maybe two more games the way that I made

62
00:02:57,588 --> 00:03:00,010
Choo Choo Mega Pack, and that is because

63
00:03:01,372 --> 00:03:02,753
I struggle with my mental health.

64
00:03:02,933 --> 00:03:05,515
This is left intentionally blank because I could not find

65
00:03:05,875 --> 00:03:06,956
an image that felt appropriate.

66
00:03:08,177 --> 00:03:09,338
I've struggled with my mental health

67
00:03:09,378 --> 00:03:10,399
for the majority of my life.

68
00:03:11,080 --> 00:03:13,902
I don't always like to admit it or accept it,

69
00:03:15,203 --> 00:03:16,164
but it is something that I know.

70
00:03:16,184 --> 00:03:18,846
It is in my family history.

71
00:03:19,447 --> 00:03:22,389
I grew up in a household where it was prevalent,

72
00:03:22,469 --> 00:03:22,990
to say the least.

73
00:03:23,679 --> 00:03:24,559
It is part of who I am.

74
00:03:26,080 --> 00:03:29,241
I understand this now, and I understood it then.

75
00:03:29,521 --> 00:03:31,301
But when I started making Choo Choo Mega Pack,

76
00:03:32,122 --> 00:03:33,062
I actively ignored it.

77
00:03:34,722 --> 00:03:36,163
So today, I would like to talk to you

78
00:03:36,403 --> 00:03:40,264
about why I ignored it, what that resulted in,

79
00:03:41,064 --> 00:03:42,865
and how I'm trying to move past that.

80
00:03:43,665 --> 00:03:45,605
But before I do that, I do have a couple disclaimers.

81
00:03:46,526 --> 00:03:48,746
Number one, I am not a mental health professional.

82
00:03:49,447 --> 00:03:51,267
I am a goof who makes video games.

83
00:03:51,707 --> 00:03:53,408
I can listen and empathize, or at least.

84
00:03:54,114 --> 00:03:55,795
try as hard as I can to do those things,

85
00:03:55,835 --> 00:03:57,975
but I am not qualified to help anyone,

86
00:03:58,195 --> 00:04:00,696
so please do not take anything I say

87
00:04:00,836 --> 00:04:02,557
as an answer or a solution.

88
00:04:02,577 --> 00:04:04,197
I only have my own experience.

89
00:04:05,337 --> 00:04:08,138
And also, because we're in the failure workshop,

90
00:04:08,899 --> 00:04:11,419
I was a little bit apprehensive about having this talk

91
00:04:11,459 --> 00:04:12,700
as part of the failure workshop

92
00:04:12,720 --> 00:04:14,300
because I wanna make something explicitly clear.

93
00:04:15,060 --> 00:04:17,501
Struggling with your mental health is not a failure.

94
00:04:17,521 --> 00:04:18,401
I am not saying that.

95
00:04:18,541 --> 00:04:19,502
I would never say that.

96
00:04:19,702 --> 00:04:20,762
I think that is gross.

97
00:04:21,522 --> 00:04:22,323
I think that is harmful.

98
00:04:22,663 --> 00:04:23,223
So hopefully.

99
00:04:24,007 --> 00:04:25,668
We are all on the same page about that.

100
00:04:35,732 --> 00:04:36,032
Thank you.

101
00:04:36,072 --> 00:04:37,212
I do have a lot more slides though.

102
00:04:37,232 --> 00:04:42,194
Okay, so let's dig into why.

103
00:04:42,214 --> 00:04:46,155
So I started my first game job in 2009.

104
00:04:46,736 --> 00:04:50,197
I cut my teeth making casual games for a variety of studios across Toronto.

105
00:04:51,117 --> 00:04:52,498
I was launching games on things like

106
00:04:53,126 --> 00:04:55,628
Big Fish and other casual digital download portals,

107
00:04:56,128 --> 00:04:58,109
Facebook and a lot of app store work,

108
00:04:58,189 --> 00:04:59,030
which is not surprising.

109
00:04:59,050 --> 00:05:02,072
And I'm extremely grateful for this chunk of my career.

110
00:05:02,092 --> 00:05:04,394
I learned a lot, helped me pay off my student debt,

111
00:05:04,434 --> 00:05:06,935
which was huge, but that was not why

112
00:05:07,035 --> 00:05:08,496
I got into the industry, right?

113
00:05:08,536 --> 00:05:09,697
Ever since I started making games,

114
00:05:09,857 --> 00:05:10,838
I wanted to do one thing.

115
00:05:10,918 --> 00:05:13,900
I wanted to make games the way I wanted to make them.

116
00:05:13,920 --> 00:05:15,081
I wanted to make them independently.

117
00:05:15,601 --> 00:05:16,582
And the context of 2008, 2009

118
00:05:16,642 --> 00:05:17,823
really only bolstered that desire.

119
00:05:21,504 --> 00:05:23,686
This is definitely not news to most of you, I'm sure,

120
00:05:23,746 --> 00:05:26,869
but in case it is, here's a little quick refresher history lesson.

121
00:05:27,490 --> 00:05:30,853
Things like digital distribution on consoles and early App Store,

122
00:05:31,714 --> 00:05:33,776
Flash game portals being a thing that existed,

123
00:05:34,037 --> 00:05:36,739
and Steam actually developing a user base

124
00:05:37,140 --> 00:05:38,681
created this weird, perfect storm

125
00:05:38,962 --> 00:05:41,504
for a new generation of indie games to reach more people.

126
00:05:42,045 --> 00:05:44,668
And as the audience grew, we developed a narrative.

127
00:05:46,057 --> 00:05:49,177
We celebrated these games for being fresh, personal alternatives

128
00:05:49,277 --> 00:05:52,458
to the increasingly cold, corporate, quote-unquote,

129
00:05:52,578 --> 00:05:54,439
traditional game industry.

130
00:05:54,599 --> 00:05:57,279
And part of that celebration involved highlighting individuals,

131
00:05:57,439 --> 00:06:00,740
often white dudes, as the sole creative forces responsible

132
00:06:00,780 --> 00:06:01,680
for these passion projects.

133
00:06:02,361 --> 00:06:06,001
And for some of us, myself included, this was a nice story to hear.

134
00:06:07,342 --> 00:06:08,242
I really latched onto it.

135
00:06:09,822 --> 00:06:10,623
This isn't surprising.

136
00:06:10,903 --> 00:06:14,223
We have a long history of idolizing lone geniuses, often

137
00:06:14,761 --> 00:06:15,342
White dudes again.

138
00:06:15,942 --> 00:06:18,685
We see it in our fiction, we see it in our businesses,

139
00:06:18,705 --> 00:06:20,546
we see it in our video games.

140
00:06:23,549 --> 00:06:25,010
So when I was lucky enough to start making games

141
00:06:25,050 --> 00:06:28,113
independently, this is really what I was aspiring to,

142
00:06:28,153 --> 00:06:29,735
whether or not I would admit it or not.

143
00:06:30,856 --> 00:06:33,498
But by mythologizing this image of the lone game developer

144
00:06:33,658 --> 00:06:35,820
and holding this ideal above everything else

145
00:06:35,940 --> 00:06:37,822
is what I think is the core.

146
00:06:38,840 --> 00:06:40,801
the core reason, or sorry, the core,

147
00:06:41,342 --> 00:06:45,264
mm-mm, the root cause of making choices

148
00:06:45,324 --> 00:06:48,286
that harmed not only myself, but others,

149
00:06:48,406 --> 00:06:52,029
and this isn't as important as those other two things,

150
00:06:52,109 --> 00:06:53,309
but also the game.

151
00:06:54,510 --> 00:06:56,031
So that's a bit broad.

152
00:06:56,872 --> 00:06:57,832
So let's get out of the heavens

153
00:06:58,553 --> 00:07:00,234
and talk about what that looked like in practice.

154
00:07:01,855 --> 00:07:02,755
So it looked a lot like this.

155
00:07:03,696 --> 00:07:06,298
Unsurprisingly, me wanting to do everything myself

156
00:07:06,578 --> 00:07:07,218
resulted in.

157
00:07:07,971 --> 00:07:09,933
an unwillingness to accept guidance from others,

158
00:07:10,274 --> 00:07:13,518
or the outright refusal of help when it was offered to me.

159
00:07:14,119 --> 00:07:17,082
Which is ridiculous because a thing that I haven't mentioned

160
00:07:17,102 --> 00:07:19,245
is I didn't build SSMP on my own.

161
00:07:19,806 --> 00:07:22,449
I worked with a group of really incredible people

162
00:07:22,509 --> 00:07:24,932
who contributed a great deal to the game.

163
00:07:25,833 --> 00:07:28,014
And I knew this about myself, and I knew this about

164
00:07:28,134 --> 00:07:29,595
the project when I was working on it.

165
00:07:29,795 --> 00:07:32,797
I was technically collaborating, but I didn't ever feel

166
00:07:33,098 --> 00:07:34,198
like I was collaborating with them,

167
00:07:34,478 --> 00:07:36,360
because I was so entrenched in this idea

168
00:07:36,840 --> 00:07:38,541
that it was my project, right?

169
00:07:38,741 --> 00:07:40,742
I was the one working full-time, I was the only one

170
00:07:40,822 --> 00:07:44,405
who could truly, fully understand the vision

171
00:07:44,505 --> 00:07:46,126
for my triangle game.

172
00:07:46,146 --> 00:07:49,428
And so over the course of development,

173
00:07:49,528 --> 00:07:51,369
I went out of my way to reinforce this idea.

174
00:07:51,389 --> 00:07:53,691
I isolated myself, I didn't leave my apartment

175
00:07:53,771 --> 00:07:55,091
for long stretches of time.

176
00:07:55,812 --> 00:08:00,074
I would organize the occasional workday here and there, but nothing really stuck.

177
00:08:01,335 --> 00:08:02,656
It was hard to justify to myself.

178
00:08:03,136 --> 00:08:04,016
I should be able to do this.

179
00:08:04,957 --> 00:08:05,897
I should be able to work from home.

180
00:08:08,579 --> 00:08:09,540
I also withdrew virtually.

181
00:08:09,920 --> 00:08:14,923
I would quietly just work on things without telling anyone what I was doing or why it

182
00:08:14,963 --> 00:08:18,405
needed to get done, and then I would pop up and say, hey, here's all this stuff I've done,

183
00:08:18,645 --> 00:08:23,308
barfing out way more information than anyone needed, wanted, or could reasonably understand,

184
00:08:23,768 --> 00:08:24,728
which only made me feel...

185
00:08:25,323 --> 00:08:26,764
Like I could not be understood even more.

186
00:08:28,605 --> 00:08:32,787
But this isolating behavior extended past just my interactions, or more specifically

187
00:08:33,407 --> 00:08:35,168
my lack of interactions with other people.

188
00:08:35,548 --> 00:08:36,529
It seeped into my process.

189
00:08:37,669 --> 00:08:39,650
I became disdainful of production methods.

190
00:08:39,871 --> 00:08:40,931
It felt like a waste of time.

191
00:08:41,752 --> 00:08:42,512
I was making the game.

192
00:08:42,612 --> 00:08:44,433
I knew what I needed to do.

193
00:08:44,453 --> 00:08:50,076
I shouldn't need some arbitrary scheduler calendar to help me reach my goals.

194
00:08:51,217 --> 00:08:51,877
It was a lie.

195
00:08:52,057 --> 00:08:54,798
Obviously this is a ridiculous way to think about building video games.

196
00:08:55,524 --> 00:08:57,285
but is what I expected from myself.

197
00:08:58,225 --> 00:08:59,706
But it wasn't real, because in reality,

198
00:09:00,387 --> 00:09:02,448
the combination of these behaviors left me feeling alone,

199
00:09:03,089 --> 00:09:05,110
with no sense of direction, and I was ashamed,

200
00:09:05,971 --> 00:09:07,552
which made me withdraw even more,

201
00:09:08,632 --> 00:09:09,573
which made that feeling stronger,

202
00:09:09,593 --> 00:09:13,696
until I didn't know where I was or what I was trying to do.

203
00:09:15,617 --> 00:09:17,839
So this was a cycle of shame and depression

204
00:09:17,979 --> 00:09:21,281
with moments of hyper-productivity that

205
00:09:22,913 --> 00:09:24,773
started really early on in development,

206
00:09:25,114 --> 00:09:27,814
way earlier than, as I was reflecting on it,

207
00:09:27,834 --> 00:09:29,015
than I actually realized.

208
00:09:30,255 --> 00:09:32,096
And it continued throughout the development of the game

209
00:09:32,316 --> 00:09:33,716
and well past its launch.

210
00:09:33,936 --> 00:09:35,237
Some of the cycles were fairly short.

211
00:09:36,557 --> 00:09:37,758
They only lasted about a few days,

212
00:09:37,898 --> 00:09:41,659
and some of them went much longer than that.

213
00:09:44,280 --> 00:09:46,861
At its worst, I was not eating, or bathing,

214
00:09:47,541 --> 00:09:48,801
or brushing my teeth, or shaving.

215
00:09:50,008 --> 00:09:55,309
Some days, just getting from my bed to the couch was a good day.

216
00:09:56,590 --> 00:09:58,170
I'd seen this in myself before, right?

217
00:09:58,190 --> 00:09:58,770
I knew what this was.

218
00:09:59,651 --> 00:10:01,831
But I thought, this should be different, right?

219
00:10:02,172 --> 00:10:06,013
I should be different because I am doing the thing that I wanted to do.

220
00:10:06,573 --> 00:10:08,513
I am doing the thing that I love.

221
00:10:09,554 --> 00:10:12,495
And the fact that it wasn't loving me back made me feel weak,

222
00:10:13,655 --> 00:10:16,556
and it made me feel lazy, and it made me feel worthless.

223
00:10:18,379 --> 00:10:19,600
And I'm not saying that there's anything wrong

224
00:10:19,720 --> 00:10:21,301
with aspiring to become something.

225
00:10:23,442 --> 00:10:27,844
But when you're too focused on the things that you lack,

226
00:10:28,025 --> 00:10:28,945
on the things that you are not,

227
00:10:29,665 --> 00:10:32,347
it becomes really easy to lose track of everything else.

228
00:10:33,568 --> 00:10:34,328
And that's what happened to me.

229
00:10:34,408 --> 00:10:35,809
And yeah, I shipped the game, sure.

230
00:10:37,150 --> 00:10:37,950
But what about the next one?

231
00:10:38,771 --> 00:10:40,211
Or the one after that, or the one after that?

232
00:10:40,412 --> 00:10:42,313
Like, how many times do I have to go through this

233
00:10:43,894 --> 00:10:45,675
before I can't do it anymore,

234
00:10:45,715 --> 00:10:47,976
before it severely hurts me?

235
00:10:50,131 --> 00:10:50,451
I don't know.

236
00:10:51,811 --> 00:10:52,992
And I don't really want to find out.

237
00:10:54,352 --> 00:10:57,913
Which brings us to how I'm trying to move past this.

238
00:10:59,233 --> 00:11:03,434
I am trying to improve my process and my relationship with my work into something that is a little

239
00:11:03,454 --> 00:11:03,954
bit healthier.

240
00:11:05,854 --> 00:11:08,455
This is not all-encompassing.

241
00:11:08,575 --> 00:11:11,235
This is a very small slice of the things that I'm doing.

242
00:11:11,295 --> 00:11:15,596
Obviously this takes place within a much broader treatment plan for myself.

243
00:11:16,813 --> 00:11:18,474
Like I said, I'm not trying to give anyone advice,

244
00:11:18,574 --> 00:11:20,075
and I wanted to keep this fairly work-centric,

245
00:11:20,115 --> 00:11:21,976
so just please keep that in mind.

246
00:11:23,698 --> 00:11:26,000
So I've tried making a habit of asking for

247
00:11:26,020 --> 00:11:27,581
and accepting help from others.

248
00:11:27,701 --> 00:11:29,502
It's not something that comes naturally to me,

249
00:11:29,742 --> 00:11:32,745
but building it into my life

250
00:11:33,265 --> 00:11:35,667
is something that I found quite beneficial.

251
00:11:36,367 --> 00:11:38,329
For example, I help organize just a small,

252
00:11:38,729 --> 00:11:39,930
peer group of game developers.

253
00:11:40,791 --> 00:11:43,113
It's not mental health-focused, but we just get together,

254
00:11:43,173 --> 00:11:45,615
and we talk about stuff, both good and bad.

255
00:11:46,682 --> 00:11:49,384
And the point of it is, we're just trying to make space

256
00:11:49,404 --> 00:11:51,965
for one another, trying to make time for each other.

257
00:11:53,226 --> 00:11:54,727
I'm really just trying to say these things out loud.

258
00:11:56,408 --> 00:11:58,530
I've also been really conscious of my physical environment

259
00:11:58,790 --> 00:11:59,711
and its impact on me.

260
00:12:00,331 --> 00:12:02,333
Keeping in line with asking others for help,

261
00:12:02,373 --> 00:12:03,633
I reached out to an old boss of mine

262
00:12:03,693 --> 00:12:05,335
who offered me a desk at a studio

263
00:12:05,395 --> 00:12:06,475
and I go there a few days a week,

264
00:12:07,136 --> 00:12:09,317
which is great if I need just a change of environment

265
00:12:09,437 --> 00:12:11,479
or to be around other human beings.

266
00:12:13,088 --> 00:12:15,770
I also brought on collaborators for my next project

267
00:12:15,970 --> 00:12:20,373
extremely early because I do not want it to be mine,

268
00:12:21,053 --> 00:12:22,114
I want it to be ours.

269
00:12:22,954 --> 00:12:24,455
I'm still guiding the project,

270
00:12:24,535 --> 00:12:26,256
but the process is a lot more conversational.

271
00:12:26,617 --> 00:12:28,077
We give each other feedback constantly,

272
00:12:28,558 --> 00:12:30,999
and who has final say is really dependent on the context.

273
00:12:31,400 --> 00:12:32,841
Obviously, it's way too early to say whether or not

274
00:12:32,881 --> 00:12:35,202
this is successful or will be successful,

275
00:12:35,302 --> 00:12:37,544
but I already think that the game is,

276
00:12:38,524 --> 00:12:40,145
at least the process is markedly better for it.

277
00:12:42,085 --> 00:12:43,867
And finally, I've been trying to mend my relationship

278
00:12:43,907 --> 00:12:45,048
with production methodologies.

279
00:12:46,990 --> 00:12:48,271
I have found something that is manageable,

280
00:12:48,791 --> 00:12:51,834
relatively lightweight, and works for me.

281
00:12:51,954 --> 00:12:53,435
It's beyond the scope of this talk,

282
00:12:53,535 --> 00:12:56,358
but I'm hopefully gonna write something about that soon.

283
00:12:56,878 --> 00:12:58,700
The thing that's really important to keep in mind

284
00:12:59,140 --> 00:13:01,422
if you are someone who is resentful of production,

285
00:13:01,562 --> 00:13:03,684
like, I don't know that it's that uncommon

286
00:13:03,784 --> 00:13:08,508
for smaller indies, is that it doesn't necessarily need

287
00:13:08,588 --> 00:13:09,969
to just be a thing that you're using to...

288
00:13:11,138 --> 00:13:16,783
make the game. It helps cut out ambiguity and anxiety and just give you a clearer picture

289
00:13:17,203 --> 00:13:22,848
when you're in the middle of development and who knows how you're ever going to make this

290
00:13:23,168 --> 00:13:31,195
goddamn thing. But I will say one of the things that my personal methodology does not have

291
00:13:31,455 --> 00:13:34,118
is Gantt charts, because they're the bad thing. They suck.

292
00:13:36,434 --> 00:13:38,016
So yeah, that's where I'm at today.

293
00:13:38,556 --> 00:13:40,958
I'm still working at it, I am chipping away at ideals

294
00:13:40,998 --> 00:13:43,400
that are doing me way more harm than good.

295
00:13:44,340 --> 00:13:45,681
I'm a work in progress, right?

296
00:13:45,982 --> 00:13:47,603
I'm not better, I don't know what that means.

297
00:13:47,643 --> 00:13:50,805
This is something that I'm likely gonna have to deal with

298
00:13:50,845 --> 00:13:54,228
for my entire life, and that is okay.

299
00:13:55,989 --> 00:13:58,871
I don't have any answers about how to live like that,

300
00:13:58,972 --> 00:14:02,314
but in my experience, regardless of whether or not

301
00:14:02,334 --> 00:14:03,475
you're struggling with your mental health,

302
00:14:04,075 --> 00:14:05,296
it's always worth reflecting on.

303
00:14:05,752 --> 00:14:08,093
the things that you want, the things that you purport to want,

304
00:14:08,974 --> 00:14:10,655
and seeing if it lines up with what you actually need.

305
00:14:11,575 --> 00:14:12,376
Because sometimes it doesn't.

306
00:14:13,116 --> 00:14:13,637
It didn't for me.

307
00:14:14,777 --> 00:14:16,759
And I'm saying that because I do not think

308
00:14:16,799 --> 00:14:18,079
that I am particularly unique.

309
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:19,700
I have...

310
00:14:24,343 --> 00:14:25,904
I guess that doesn't really match the tone, huh?

311
00:14:27,905 --> 00:14:30,087
I have no doubt in my mind that there are other people

312
00:14:30,367 --> 00:14:32,528
either in this room or at this conference.

313
00:14:33,117 --> 00:14:35,277
in this industry that have gone through, are going through,

314
00:14:35,337 --> 00:14:37,778
or will go through something similar to what I described.

315
00:14:38,298 --> 00:14:39,638
Not the same, but it doesn't really matter.

316
00:14:41,179 --> 00:14:42,059
And if you are one of those people,

317
00:14:42,139 --> 00:14:44,620
I just wanted to say that I hope you feel seen.

318
00:14:45,080 --> 00:14:46,420
You are why I wanted to give this talk.

319
00:14:46,920 --> 00:14:48,281
I don't think the world needs more games

320
00:14:48,301 --> 00:14:49,601
about triangles and shooting,

321
00:14:50,061 --> 00:14:51,662
but I do think the industry needs your voices

322
00:14:51,942 --> 00:14:52,662
and your perspectives.

323
00:14:53,302 --> 00:14:55,563
And the thought of us not being able to hear them

324
00:14:55,643 --> 00:14:58,504
because you are trying to wear too many hats

325
00:14:58,564 --> 00:14:59,804
or you're trying to shove yourself into one

326
00:14:59,824 --> 00:15:01,484
that doesn't fit properly,

327
00:15:03,479 --> 00:15:04,200
I think that's heartbreaking.

328
00:15:05,561 --> 00:15:07,803
So I hope something I've said resonated with some of you

329
00:15:07,823 --> 00:15:08,224
in some way.

330
00:15:08,264 --> 00:15:11,106
But please do not listen to me for most things.

331
00:15:11,727 --> 00:15:12,668
Here are some resources.

332
00:15:12,848 --> 00:15:14,210
It's very GDC-centric again.

333
00:15:14,910 --> 00:15:16,572
Both Checkpoint and Take This have

334
00:15:17,273 --> 00:15:19,615
aggregated a lot of really great information

335
00:15:19,715 --> 00:15:21,837
for people who are either struggling with mental health

336
00:15:21,957 --> 00:15:23,358
or know other people who are struggling

337
00:15:23,378 --> 00:15:23,979
with their mental health.

338
00:15:24,386 --> 00:15:27,530
Also, there is an IGDA-led roundtable on Thursday

339
00:15:27,570 --> 00:15:28,671
at 2 p.m. in the South Hall,

340
00:15:28,912 --> 00:15:30,574
if that is something you feel comfortable going to.

341
00:15:30,594 --> 00:15:33,517
I went to one last year and it was extremely cathartic.

342
00:15:33,877 --> 00:15:35,319
It was hard, but I enjoyed it.

343
00:15:35,339 --> 00:15:37,221
Enjoy is not the right word.

344
00:15:39,224 --> 00:15:40,285
But that's not for everybody.

345
00:15:41,827 --> 00:15:42,828
Yeah, so that's it.

346
00:15:42,968 --> 00:15:43,890
Thank you so much for your time.

347
00:15:57,860 --> 00:15:59,081
Thanks.

348
00:15:59,281 --> 00:16:01,143
There's my contact information if you want.

349
00:16:01,403 --> 00:16:01,784
Bye.

350
00:16:04,246 --> 00:16:04,867
My name is Juan.

351
00:16:05,047 --> 00:16:08,330
I'm 26 years old and I'm the co-founder,

352
00:16:09,031 --> 00:16:10,953
creative director and business person

353
00:16:11,193 --> 00:16:13,435
at a small indie studio based in Spain.

354
00:16:13,455 --> 00:16:14,296
It's called Team Gotham.

355
00:16:15,437 --> 00:16:17,940
First of all, I want to say thank you for having me here.

356
00:16:19,544 --> 00:16:21,765
It's pretty much an honor for me.

357
00:16:22,225 --> 00:16:26,207
And second, I want to apologize if I made mistakes

358
00:16:26,267 --> 00:16:26,848
during my talk.

359
00:16:27,328 --> 00:16:28,809
English is not my first language,

360
00:16:29,449 --> 00:16:30,690
so I know I made mistakes.

361
00:16:31,030 --> 00:16:32,591
So yeah, apologize for that.

362
00:16:34,892 --> 00:16:37,713
This talk is going to be at postmortem

363
00:16:38,374 --> 00:16:41,755
not only on our previous last game release,

364
00:16:41,835 --> 00:16:45,597
but on the whole history of our company, Team Gotham.

365
00:16:46,485 --> 00:16:51,769
And it's going to be a story about making loads of mistakes that led us to make desperate

366
00:16:51,809 --> 00:16:59,016
decisions that led us to loads of anxiety and sleepless nights in the past few months.

367
00:17:00,116 --> 00:17:08,924
As this is pretty raw, still is pretty recent, I expect this talk, like me being here, to

368
00:17:08,964 --> 00:17:14,349
be kind of therapy to get some closure about all this.

369
00:17:15,589 --> 00:17:21,431
recent events and also help, of course, others that may be in a similar situation, hopefully.

370
00:17:24,251 --> 00:17:30,253
So the story begins when we founded the studio, Team Gotham, back in 2013.

371
00:17:30,873 --> 00:17:38,055
We were starting at university and we were making mobile games, prototypes, and we quickly

372
00:17:38,295 --> 00:17:42,397
jumped into PC development with a game called The Guest.

373
00:17:43,062 --> 00:17:44,923
which is a first-person exploration game,

374
00:17:44,943 --> 00:17:46,605
a really humble, classic thing,

375
00:17:47,205 --> 00:17:50,128
somewhere between Gone Home and The Room,

376
00:17:50,948 --> 00:17:51,329
if you may.

377
00:17:52,570 --> 00:17:55,012
And yeah, so did we know what we were doing back then?

378
00:17:55,712 --> 00:17:59,796
Kind of yes, because we knew how to do 3D modeling,

379
00:17:59,896 --> 00:18:01,497
we knew how to do programming,

380
00:18:01,697 --> 00:18:03,219
we knew basics on design,

381
00:18:03,339 --> 00:18:05,380
so development was covered,

382
00:18:05,461 --> 00:18:08,643
but hell no, like when we finished college,

383
00:18:10,726 --> 00:18:12,347
We didn't know anything about the industry.

384
00:18:12,467 --> 00:18:15,328
We didn't know how to get the game noticed,

385
00:18:15,888 --> 00:18:20,089
and we were trying everything to make that happen.

386
00:18:20,190 --> 00:18:22,490
We were trying to send out press releases,

387
00:18:22,610 --> 00:18:24,851
going to events, pitch to publishers,

388
00:18:25,511 --> 00:18:28,012
all those things that weren't working at all.

389
00:18:28,632 --> 00:18:32,454
So we got into this sense of desperation,

390
00:18:32,734 --> 00:18:34,074
and we collapsed.

391
00:18:34,875 --> 00:18:37,976
So we say, oh hey, a publisher might help us, right?

392
00:18:39,373 --> 00:18:43,355
people say a publisher can help, so that may be a good idea.

393
00:18:45,916 --> 00:18:49,057
After all this process of desperation where we collapsed,

394
00:18:49,097 --> 00:18:52,559
we traveled to many events back in Europe,

395
00:18:53,439 --> 00:18:56,680
and we landed a publisher in a moment of huge desperation.

396
00:18:56,720 --> 00:18:58,821
It was like the last resource we had.

397
00:18:59,881 --> 00:19:02,182
Because we didn't have real resources.

398
00:19:02,202 --> 00:19:04,043
We didn't have any money or savings.

399
00:19:04,323 --> 00:19:05,303
We were just students.

400
00:19:06,446 --> 00:19:11,950
So landing a publisher in this situation was a good thing and a bad thing.

401
00:19:13,671 --> 00:19:25,099
So being desperate is the feeling of showing a hopeless sense that a situation is so bad that it's impossible to deal with.

402
00:19:25,379 --> 00:19:29,101
And also a feeling of great need or desire for something.

403
00:19:29,682 --> 00:19:31,083
I would say that we had...

404
00:19:32,441 --> 00:19:36,004
mixed feeling between these two definitions of the word.

405
00:19:36,704 --> 00:19:43,210
And yeah, this whole situation led us to this desperate decision number one,

406
00:19:43,770 --> 00:19:46,832
which was signing a good deal in short term with this publisher,

407
00:19:46,852 --> 00:19:49,635
but it was bad in the long run for us.

408
00:19:51,536 --> 00:19:55,899
So again, we had no resources, we had nothing was working,

409
00:19:55,960 --> 00:19:59,302
everything we were trying, and we were collapsed.

410
00:20:00,056 --> 00:20:03,298
at that time, so when we were negotiating with this publisher,

411
00:20:04,419 --> 00:20:06,060
we did a lot of things wrong.

412
00:20:06,641 --> 00:20:14,206
We budgeted wrong, and we rejected

413
00:20:14,246 --> 00:20:18,409
to have any revenue share in the short term, which

414
00:20:18,469 --> 00:20:21,891
means they had 100% recoup policy, which

415
00:20:21,951 --> 00:20:26,534
means publishers have to recoup the investment.

416
00:20:28,564 --> 00:20:31,385
and only then you will see some profit of it.

417
00:20:32,405 --> 00:20:36,266
It was good in the short term because it was going to allow us

418
00:20:36,326 --> 00:20:41,447
to do things immediately and build a studio properly,

419
00:20:41,707 --> 00:20:43,428
hire some people, stuff like that.

420
00:20:44,128 --> 00:20:48,849
But this feeling of being anxious about getting money,

421
00:20:49,129 --> 00:20:52,810
it wasn't greed, I would say, but we were students

422
00:20:52,950 --> 00:20:55,390
and we wanted to build a thing properly.

423
00:20:55,990 --> 00:20:57,271
So this anxious feeling...

424
00:20:59,014 --> 00:21:03,976
didn't allow us to sit back and relax and take a lot of things

425
00:21:04,336 --> 00:21:07,797
and ask people that were more experienced than us

426
00:21:07,877 --> 00:21:09,058
and just stop thinking.

427
00:21:09,538 --> 00:21:10,438
So we were anxious.

428
00:21:10,518 --> 00:21:13,559
We ran into the deal, and we signed the deal.

429
00:21:14,039 --> 00:21:19,261
So three years from that, from releasing the game

430
00:21:19,641 --> 00:21:20,922
and 25,000 copies after launch, we've

431
00:21:20,982 --> 00:21:23,762
seen no money from this game yet.

432
00:21:23,903 --> 00:21:27,384
And it's not expecting to change any time soon.

433
00:21:27,404 --> 00:21:28,204
I mean, it's not like the game.

434
00:21:28,920 --> 00:21:32,180
is a hit and will be rich or something,

435
00:21:32,240 --> 00:21:35,601
but paying bills is also nice.

436
00:21:37,602 --> 00:21:39,502
But yeah, that's how we feel now,

437
00:21:39,562 --> 00:21:41,543
but back then was like, hey, who cares?

438
00:21:41,663 --> 00:21:43,983
Like a game didn't work out that well,

439
00:21:44,023 --> 00:21:45,644
but we have plenty of money in the bank,

440
00:21:46,184 --> 00:21:48,104
let's make a new game, whatever.

441
00:21:48,364 --> 00:21:53,545
So we wanted to overlap the ending

442
00:21:53,645 --> 00:21:55,626
of the production of The Guest with the...

443
00:21:57,036 --> 00:22:00,157
with a new game, with a new pre-production of the game.

444
00:22:00,177 --> 00:22:02,018
And we asked ourselves, like,

445
00:22:02,118 --> 00:22:03,579
shouldn't we take a break before that?

446
00:22:03,599 --> 00:22:06,561
I mean, we've been making this game for two years,

447
00:22:07,061 --> 00:22:11,323
and it should be nice to have a break

448
00:22:11,383 --> 00:22:14,985
and just stay away from things for some time.

449
00:22:15,566 --> 00:22:19,068
But at that time, money blinded us badly,

450
00:22:19,188 --> 00:22:22,770
and we were basically slaves of this money.

451
00:22:23,290 --> 00:22:25,211
We were thinking time equals money.

452
00:22:25,994 --> 00:22:29,557
and vacation equals nonsense, which is absolutely wrong.

453
00:22:30,318 --> 00:22:34,521
And that had really bad consequences after that.

454
00:22:34,661 --> 00:22:37,564
But we didn't allow ourselves to stop at this point

455
00:22:37,584 --> 00:22:39,025
because money was running out.

456
00:22:39,865 --> 00:22:43,688
So we started the production of our last game,

457
00:22:43,708 --> 00:22:47,572
it's called Solo, which is an introspective puzzle

458
00:22:47,612 --> 00:22:49,633
adventure about love relationships

459
00:22:49,893 --> 00:22:53,136
and how love affects our everyday life.

460
00:22:54,157 --> 00:22:54,257
And.

461
00:22:55,100 --> 00:22:58,022
What happened six months into development?

462
00:22:58,763 --> 00:23:02,605
We spent $45,000 into a vertical slice,

463
00:23:02,665 --> 00:23:07,448
which was kind of like the half of the budget we have.

464
00:23:07,468 --> 00:23:09,429
And the game was absolute shit.

465
00:23:09,569 --> 00:23:10,530
Game was boring.

466
00:23:11,350 --> 00:23:12,491
It's like doing homework.

467
00:23:14,052 --> 00:23:15,973
So wow, why did this happen?

468
00:23:16,213 --> 00:23:19,955
Because communication was inexistent.

469
00:23:19,975 --> 00:23:20,716
It was really poor.

470
00:23:21,622 --> 00:23:27,964
We were burned out. We never stopped to, as I say, sit back and think about things.

471
00:23:28,064 --> 00:23:35,967
We were continuously doing things with this anxious feeling of money's running out, money's running out.

472
00:23:36,087 --> 00:23:36,987
We have to do stuff.

473
00:23:39,408 --> 00:23:45,530
So yeah, I remember one day I came to the studio and I asked people like,

474
00:23:45,830 --> 00:23:50,432
how do you feel about the game? And no one was happy about it.

475
00:23:51,018 --> 00:23:54,361
but we never talked about it before.

476
00:23:55,301 --> 00:23:58,924
So yeah, it was too late.

477
00:23:59,285 --> 00:24:00,566
We needed to shift directions now.

478
00:24:01,647 --> 00:24:06,411
New design, a new business plan, but money was running out,

479
00:24:06,591 --> 00:24:07,031
for real.

480
00:24:07,792 --> 00:24:10,074
We spent half of what we had.

481
00:24:11,375 --> 00:24:13,056
There was no time at all.

482
00:24:14,397 --> 00:24:16,859
And we already pitched publishers,

483
00:24:17,360 --> 00:24:19,261
and they, of course, rejected that.

484
00:24:20,133 --> 00:24:31,957
trash game we had. So this situation again, this action, anxious, sorry, situation of

485
00:24:32,117 --> 00:24:37,798
desperation of collapsing again, led us to the desperate decision number two, which was

486
00:24:37,858 --> 00:24:43,740
making a crowdfunding campaign. We were super scared about a crowdfunding campaign, but

487
00:24:43,780 --> 00:24:46,361
we had no other option to get money as AIP.

488
00:24:47,537 --> 00:24:51,978
So we approached FIG, which is a crowdfunding, crowdinvestment platform,

489
00:24:52,619 --> 00:24:55,680
and they shared the vision of the game.

490
00:24:55,700 --> 00:24:58,161
We were excited about it, so that was great.

491
00:24:59,701 --> 00:25:05,663
But we were still really, really afraid of doing a crowdfunding campaign,

492
00:25:05,703 --> 00:25:10,865
so we budgeted the campaign way below what we needed,

493
00:25:11,105 --> 00:25:13,306
because we were scared about not getting to the goal.

494
00:25:14,574 --> 00:25:18,257
That would let us almost no money left for marketing and PR actions.

495
00:25:20,599 --> 00:25:25,723
One thing also is that during the campaign, in the middle of it, we got stuck.

496
00:25:26,304 --> 00:25:30,547
Like, money was not rising and the goal was approaching.

497
00:25:31,087 --> 00:25:33,890
So Fick came out with a kind of a solution.

498
00:25:34,090 --> 00:25:36,812
He bring an investor, and guess what?

499
00:25:37,112 --> 00:25:39,494
Investor wanted 100% recoup policy again.

500
00:25:39,755 --> 00:25:42,877
So, one year after launch, again.

501
00:25:43,588 --> 00:25:45,728
We have seen no money from game sales,

502
00:25:46,648 --> 00:25:48,469
and it's not expected to change anytime soon.

503
00:25:50,509 --> 00:25:54,130
It's important to understand that we took these decisions

504
00:25:55,430 --> 00:25:58,131
thinking that we're the best for the studio at that time,

505
00:25:59,111 --> 00:26:02,532
and that was the only options we had all the time.

506
00:26:04,232 --> 00:26:05,773
And well, it's not only that.

507
00:26:05,813 --> 00:26:08,473
It's not only about these deals, but it's also the gap.

508
00:26:08,933 --> 00:26:09,273
You never.

509
00:26:10,692 --> 00:26:11,913
You know the industry's bad.

510
00:26:12,213 --> 00:26:14,954
It's really hard to get your game on Steam, blah, blah, blah.

511
00:26:15,314 --> 00:26:17,995
But you never expect your game to be that bad.

512
00:26:19,076 --> 00:26:21,076
Press is talking great about your game,

513
00:26:21,156 --> 00:26:22,317
but no one's buying it.

514
00:26:23,977 --> 00:26:28,699
So that's also something that emotionally, it's on you.

515
00:26:29,220 --> 00:26:33,721
So the thing is, the abusive 100% recoup deals

516
00:26:33,801 --> 00:26:35,662
killed us in some way, and maybe killing

517
00:26:35,702 --> 00:26:37,383
other people, all the studios.

518
00:26:39,504 --> 00:26:42,146
We have no money in the bank left in the company account,

519
00:26:42,286 --> 00:26:44,628
so all the expenses are out of our pockets,

520
00:26:44,688 --> 00:26:46,329
like being here or going there.

521
00:26:47,309 --> 00:26:51,973
And the games we made wasn't huge hits,

522
00:26:52,333 --> 00:26:54,975
but still we'll be paying some bills, which is nice.

523
00:26:57,697 --> 00:27:01,739
I often ask myself if we would be at the same point

524
00:27:02,220 --> 00:27:06,843
if that first desperate deal hadn't been that desperate.

525
00:27:07,486 --> 00:27:13,710
And honestly, I think yes, because this talk is not a rant on publishers or 100% recruit

526
00:27:13,890 --> 00:27:15,171
deals, which I think they suck.

527
00:27:16,352 --> 00:27:23,057
It's more a rant on us, talking out loud about all the stuff we made wrong, which is a bunch.

528
00:27:23,937 --> 00:27:29,481
Like I said, we budget things wrong, we scope things wrong, we didn't communicate, which

529
00:27:29,561 --> 00:27:32,903
is the most important thing that we...

530
00:27:33,498 --> 00:27:38,299
we didn't do, I think a good producer is not only the one who is delivering the game on time,

531
00:27:38,519 --> 00:27:43,601
it's also the one who has like a human approach to the people,

532
00:27:44,501 --> 00:27:47,902
and a sensitive approach to the people who's working with,

533
00:27:47,922 --> 00:27:56,385
and before asking how's work, asking how do you feel, how's life, are you okay, all that things.

534
00:27:57,025 --> 00:27:59,586
And that's the lesson I learned and I'm trying to apply.

535
00:28:00,386 --> 00:28:02,226
in my everyday life, not only in games,

536
00:28:02,386 --> 00:28:04,187
but with friends and family.

537
00:28:05,187 --> 00:28:08,448
So I think no, life would be the same,

538
00:28:08,568 --> 00:28:10,869
because also we were making games

539
00:28:10,909 --> 00:28:12,389
that maybe no one wanted to buy.

540
00:28:12,729 --> 00:28:16,870
So it's good acknowledging that the desperate deals

541
00:28:17,090 --> 00:28:19,131
are only like the turning points of the story,

542
00:28:19,411 --> 00:28:23,492
but our mistakes is what led us to those points.

543
00:28:25,552 --> 00:28:26,553
So right now,

544
00:28:28,220 --> 00:28:32,102
We have made no money from game sales since 2013.

545
00:28:33,123 --> 00:28:36,765
We have made huge mistakes out of huge desperation

546
00:28:37,385 --> 00:28:41,347
that led us to sign bad deals for us.

547
00:28:42,027 --> 00:28:44,469
We lost one partner and one employee in the last year.

548
00:28:44,489 --> 00:28:48,931
Now I doubt constantly of my capacities

549
00:28:48,971 --> 00:28:51,412
to be even talking here at GDC.

550
00:28:53,838 --> 00:28:56,759
I've been like unhappy, suffering anxiety,

551
00:28:56,779 --> 00:29:00,761
uncomfortable with myself since Solo came out last year.

552
00:29:01,901 --> 00:29:02,881
I don't play games anymore.

553
00:29:02,901 --> 00:29:05,222
I actually hate games right now.

554
00:29:05,962 --> 00:29:07,783
I'm struggling with game dev a lot.

555
00:29:07,943 --> 00:29:13,065
I'm trying to park game dev for a while in my life.

