00:29:37,774 --> 00:29:40,074
So yeah, I love you and thank you.

563
00:29:45,936 --> 00:29:47,697
My name is Charlie Price.

564
00:29:47,857 --> 00:29:49,998
I'm the co-founder and creative director of Hidden Variable.

565
00:29:50,038 --> 00:29:50,538
We're a small.

566
00:29:51,052 --> 00:29:55,258
Independent studio based down in Los Angeles when we were first founded in 2010

567
00:29:55,838 --> 00:29:58,922
We mostly made mobile puzzle games like baguette and tic tactics

568
00:29:59,383 --> 00:30:02,307
We worked with servo on threes to bring to Android and Xbox among other things

569
00:30:02,767 --> 00:30:06,352
But more recently we're most well known for the game skull girls mobile

570
00:30:07,413 --> 00:30:07,793
trailer here

571
00:30:08,497 --> 00:30:10,359
For those who aren't aware, the original Skullgirls game

572
00:30:10,379 --> 00:30:11,339
was developed by Lab Zero.

573
00:30:11,379 --> 00:30:13,601
It's a 2D hand-animated fighting game

574
00:30:14,582 --> 00:30:17,364
that was released back in 2012.

575
00:30:17,704 --> 00:30:19,785
We approached them about going through and bringing

576
00:30:19,825 --> 00:30:20,586
Skullgirls to mobile.

577
00:30:20,606 --> 00:30:22,667
And part of our goal there was to go through and make

578
00:30:22,707 --> 00:30:24,729
fighting games more accessible for folks that otherwise find

579
00:30:24,749 --> 00:30:26,930
them intimidating, but without compromising their depth

580
00:30:26,970 --> 00:30:29,132
and a lot of the creativity that you ultimately

581
00:30:29,172 --> 00:30:31,734
have when you're playing fighting games at a high level.

582
00:30:32,454 --> 00:30:34,275
So as a result, while we were able to take over

583
00:30:34,295 --> 00:30:35,616
a lot of the animations that they had already

584
00:30:35,636 --> 00:30:36,617
built, these beautiful animations.

585
00:30:37,358 --> 00:30:43,101
And some of the combat mechanics we had to make a lot of adjustments to go through and map it over to mobile native controls

586
00:30:43,181 --> 00:30:46,623
So mostly taps and swipes no virtual thumb sticks or anything like that

587
00:30:47,483 --> 00:30:52,266
In addition to all that stuff the mobile game unlike the console game was a free-to-play RPG

588
00:30:52,446 --> 00:30:55,127
So there was a whole host of additional systems. We had to go through and build

589
00:30:56,208 --> 00:30:58,750
progression systems, skill trees, signature abilities,

590
00:30:59,651 --> 00:31:03,293
social features like chat, live events like daily events,

591
00:31:03,394 --> 00:31:05,315
and prize fights and rift battles,

592
00:31:05,395 --> 00:31:07,297
and all the bells and whistles you would normally expect

593
00:31:08,037 --> 00:31:08,838
from a free to play game.

594
00:31:09,518 --> 00:31:11,120
And it's a pretty ambitious thing for a small team,

595
00:31:11,140 --> 00:31:12,901
and I'm incredibly proud of all the stuff

596
00:31:12,921 --> 00:31:13,922
that we were able to accomplish.

597
00:31:14,462 --> 00:31:15,923
However, this talk is not about all the things

598
00:31:15,943 --> 00:31:16,444
that we're proud of.

599
00:31:16,604 --> 00:31:19,186
Instead, this talk's about the time that we accidentally

600
00:31:19,206 --> 00:31:20,627
went and deleted all of our users' data.

601
00:31:22,051 --> 00:31:25,254
So, a brief history of how we got there.

602
00:31:25,854 --> 00:31:29,397
So actually, Skullgirls started back in 2014 at GDC.

603
00:31:30,157 --> 00:31:32,379
We decided to sign up with Autumn Games to go through and make this happen.

604
00:31:32,699 --> 00:31:35,802
A year later we were approached by Line, who were interested in going through and publishing

605
00:31:35,822 --> 00:31:38,684
the game, particularly to distribute it in Korea and Japan, which sounded awesome to

606
00:31:38,804 --> 00:31:42,227
us because those are really notoriously difficult territories to crack.

607
00:31:43,068 --> 00:31:44,509
And, you know, again, fast forwarding,

608
00:31:45,250 --> 00:31:47,072
spring 2017, we were able to go through

609
00:31:47,092 --> 00:31:48,333
and launch the game under the Lion label

610
00:31:49,254 --> 00:31:51,316
in the US and mostly worldwide,

611
00:31:51,356 --> 00:31:53,278
except for a planned launch in Korea and Japan

612
00:31:53,298 --> 00:31:54,720
a little bit later on in the year.

613
00:31:55,220 --> 00:31:56,702
When we launched, everything was going really well.

614
00:31:57,082 --> 00:31:58,824
The game was really well received, good reviews.

615
00:31:58,904 --> 00:32:01,006
We were getting a lot of organic downloads, which is awesome.

616
00:32:02,363 --> 00:32:03,864
But there were some challenges.

617
00:32:05,044 --> 00:32:07,265
Line was going through a little bit of corporate drama at the time.

618
00:32:07,285 --> 00:32:10,387
They'd recently gone through and acquired a new game studio, and as a result they were

619
00:32:10,427 --> 00:32:15,489
reshuffling some stuff, and so a lot of things were frozen, which included our marketing

620
00:32:15,529 --> 00:32:15,849
budget.

621
00:32:16,750 --> 00:32:20,171
So while we were getting good organic users, we knew we needed to be kind of figuring out

622
00:32:20,211 --> 00:32:23,113
what our user acquisition plan was going to be in order to make sure that we were sustainable

623
00:32:23,793 --> 00:32:24,333
moving forward.

624
00:32:24,673 --> 00:32:28,475
So while we were hopeful that that would resolve itself, it became pretty evident that it wasn't.

625
00:32:28,775 --> 00:32:31,796
So we made the tough decision to part ways with Line forever.

626
00:32:32,296 --> 00:32:36,077
So that came with its own set of challenges across the board.

627
00:32:36,617 --> 00:32:37,838
First off was a technical challenge.

628
00:32:38,318 --> 00:32:43,059
We had basically originally planned to go through and like kind of pluck a back end off the shelf

629
00:32:43,119 --> 00:32:44,579
and be able to use a lot of existing features.

630
00:32:44,619 --> 00:32:48,640
But when we partnered with Line, they basically required us to build something from the ground up

631
00:32:48,680 --> 00:32:50,321
to all of their exacting requirements.

632
00:32:50,721 --> 00:32:54,642
And now that we were migrating, we had to somehow untangle all of that stuff

633
00:32:54,802 --> 00:32:57,643
and migrate it over to AWS so that we could go through and manage it ourselves.

634
00:32:58,844 --> 00:33:02,867
We were fortunate that we were able to find an expert back-end partner who knew all these things backwards and forwards

635
00:33:02,887 --> 00:33:06,331
so we could kind of learn on the go with them and then we could focus on the client-side stuff.

636
00:33:06,931 --> 00:33:11,776
The client-side stuff had its own challenges. In an ideal world, Line would just transfer the game over to us and players,

637
00:33:12,096 --> 00:33:17,261
you know, one day the publisher would change from one company to another and players wouldn't be the wiser, they'd just be able to carry on.

638
00:33:17,641 --> 00:33:20,324
Line was not comfortable doing that for data privacy reasons,

639
00:33:20,664 --> 00:33:24,027
nor were they comfortable just transferring all of the user data over to us behind the scenes.

640
00:33:24,368 --> 00:33:27,291
So instead, what we had to do was let them opt in,

641
00:33:27,511 --> 00:33:30,914
which basically meant that, imagine logging into a game and saying,

642
00:33:30,974 --> 00:33:33,016
hey, by the way, this game's going to shut down in two months,

643
00:33:33,076 --> 00:33:34,978
but it's not going to go away. There's going to be a new game.

644
00:33:35,338 --> 00:33:37,621
All we need is for you to put in your email address and your password,

645
00:33:37,641 --> 00:33:39,262
and then later when this game shuts down,

646
00:33:39,583 --> 00:33:42,185
in the new game you can log in with this stuff and everything's going to be fine.

647
00:33:43,126 --> 00:33:45,626
So we did everything we could to try and make that a palatable thing.

648
00:33:45,666 --> 00:33:47,327
We incentivized it, gave people rewards.

649
00:33:47,967 --> 00:33:51,148
But when it was all said and done, when we finally did the migration, we went from 500,000

650
00:33:52,068 --> 00:33:54,069
total users that we had before down to 50,000.

651
00:33:54,609 --> 00:33:59,831
So that was a pretty big hit, but they were our most engaged users, we told ourselves.

652
00:33:59,851 --> 00:34:00,511
So that's great.

653
00:34:01,431 --> 00:34:02,252
And it's time to move on.

654
00:34:02,332 --> 00:34:02,912
Time to move forward.

655
00:34:02,952 --> 00:34:03,552
It's a new beginning.

656
00:34:03,832 --> 00:34:04,492
We're going to be fine.

657
00:34:04,693 --> 00:34:05,353
It's going to be fine.

658
00:34:06,434 --> 00:34:09,076
So in January of 2018, right after we did this migration,

659
00:34:09,316 --> 00:34:10,217
things were looking pretty good.

660
00:34:11,038 --> 00:34:12,880
We had gone through and relaunched successfully,

661
00:34:12,940 --> 00:34:14,361
the migration, which is complicated,

662
00:34:14,421 --> 00:34:15,542
had turned out, it went okay.

663
00:34:16,303 --> 00:34:17,824
We were doing some proper user acquisition,

664
00:34:17,864 --> 00:34:19,286
we'd been saving up our marketing dollars,

665
00:34:19,346 --> 00:34:21,128
and we invested and we were able to get

666
00:34:21,148 --> 00:34:23,149
almost 200,000 users in our first month, which is awesome.

667
00:34:24,250 --> 00:34:25,692
And our back-end partner was handling

668
00:34:25,732 --> 00:34:26,993
all the different ups and downs that come

669
00:34:27,013 --> 00:34:28,655
with running a live game, so that was really good.

670
00:34:29,048 --> 00:34:30,529
And then we heard word through the grapevine

671
00:34:30,549 --> 00:34:32,270
that we might have an app store feature that was coming up.

672
00:34:32,330 --> 00:34:33,651
And so we're like, thank god, this is perfect.

673
00:34:34,311 --> 00:34:36,372
So what we did, just to be safe, we

674
00:34:36,412 --> 00:34:38,473
decided to go through and double our server bandwidth,

675
00:34:38,493 --> 00:34:39,494
just to make sure that we could handle

676
00:34:39,514 --> 00:34:41,575
the hopeful influx of all these new users

677
00:34:41,595 --> 00:34:42,456
we're going to be dealing with.

678
00:34:43,316 --> 00:34:44,957
So in general, things are going really, really well.

679
00:34:46,145 --> 00:34:53,107
So 0800 Friday, February 2nd, 2018, mere days before this purported feature, I get a phone

680
00:34:53,127 --> 00:34:57,968
call from one of our engineers who regretfully informs me that our back-end partner, instead

681
00:34:57,988 --> 00:35:02,649
of provisioning a new shard, accidentally reprovisioned our live shard, effectively

682
00:35:02,689 --> 00:35:05,650
reformatting it and wiping all of our user data.

683
00:35:07,951 --> 00:35:08,691
So I took a moment.

684
00:35:11,111 --> 00:35:12,952
And I said, okay, we're going to be down for a bit.

685
00:35:12,972 --> 00:35:13,512
That's awful.

686
00:35:13,772 --> 00:35:13,832
Oh!

687
00:35:14,726 --> 00:35:15,426
What about the backups?

688
00:35:15,446 --> 00:35:17,347
How long will it take for us to go through and restore from our backups?

689
00:35:18,128 --> 00:35:19,108
And that was the kicker.

690
00:35:19,869 --> 00:35:20,709
There were no backups.

691
00:35:21,669 --> 00:35:24,551
Our partner had said they were doing backups, but we had never bothered to check.

692
00:35:25,671 --> 00:35:28,913
And so as a result, we were left with no data at all.

693
00:35:29,473 --> 00:35:32,014
It was a pretty rough day, as you might imagine.

694
00:35:32,915 --> 00:35:35,076
We'd been through so much getting to this point.

695
00:35:37,027 --> 00:35:40,549
We, you know, not only building the game, which seemingly was like a great game and

696
00:35:40,569 --> 00:35:43,692
people dug it, and then we had to migrate and then we just rebuilt it and we're right

697
00:35:43,732 --> 00:35:47,034
on the cusp of this great new moment for us and somehow we just torpedoed ourselves.

698
00:35:48,055 --> 00:35:50,637
So you know, it's pretty disheartening for the team as a whole.

699
00:35:51,178 --> 00:35:54,961
And there was a very real temptation for us to want to go through and basically absolve

700
00:35:55,001 --> 00:35:55,941
ourselves of blame.

701
00:35:56,021 --> 00:35:59,384
After all, we weren't the ones that pushed the button or pulled the plug or whatever

702
00:35:59,404 --> 00:36:00,185
metaphor you want to use.

703
00:36:00,912 --> 00:36:04,452
However, it was really important for us to go through and reflect on the fact that ultimately,

704
00:36:04,592 --> 00:36:06,373
even though they're our partner, they're our responsibility.

705
00:36:06,413 --> 00:36:07,653
This game is our responsibility.

706
00:36:07,693 --> 00:36:11,814
We are responsible to our players, are responsible to our customers, to go through and maintain

707
00:36:11,834 --> 00:36:12,914
the sanctity of their data.

708
00:36:13,674 --> 00:36:16,915
I know a lot of these things can feel like an act of God in the moment, but reflecting

709
00:36:16,975 --> 00:36:19,135
on it, there are always opportunities.

710
00:36:19,195 --> 00:36:21,776
Maybe we couldn't have prevented the action itself, but there's definitely things we could

711
00:36:21,796 --> 00:36:25,377
have done in order to go through and prevent the consequences from being as dire.

712
00:36:26,437 --> 00:36:28,077
It was our responsibility to go through and make it right.

713
00:36:29,485 --> 00:36:30,165
Assessing the damage.

714
00:36:30,865 --> 00:36:31,966
So there was some good news.

715
00:36:32,406 --> 00:36:36,067
We still had that 50,000 users worth of data.

716
00:36:36,107 --> 00:36:39,088
It's a month old, but some data's better than no data, so that's something.

717
00:36:39,928 --> 00:36:44,210
And then we had this activity log, which was basically a separate server, thank God, that

718
00:36:44,250 --> 00:36:48,091
was used to track any time someone opened a mystery box or a character leveled up, major

719
00:36:48,131 --> 00:36:48,791
progression events.

720
00:36:48,811 --> 00:36:53,153
And we realized we could run a script on that server in order to basically go through and

721
00:36:53,253 --> 00:36:55,353
roughly reconstruct most of the data for our players.

722
00:36:55,393 --> 00:36:57,634
So it seemed like maybe this is all going to be okay.

723
00:36:57,814 --> 00:36:58,674
We're just going to get through it.

724
00:36:58,694 --> 00:36:59,135
It'll be great.

725
00:37:00,175 --> 00:37:01,015
But there was some bad news.

726
