00:37:27,260 --> 00:37:29,640
out what actually happened and what our options were and what was going on.

753
00:37:30,141 --> 00:37:31,881
But it was time for us to go through and deliver the news.

754
00:37:32,622 --> 00:37:36,123
So I wrote this long forum post explaining everything.

755
00:37:37,083 --> 00:37:41,124
And I won't go through the whole thing, but the main tenets were we wanted to take responsibility

756
00:37:41,164 --> 00:37:41,725
for what happened.

757
00:37:42,281 --> 00:37:46,224
let them know what was going on, give them kind of the full story of how we got to this point,

758
00:37:46,544 --> 00:37:49,687
and reassure them that we were going to do everything in our power to go through and regain their trust,

759
00:37:50,207 --> 00:37:53,470
and obviously apologizing profusely. That's kind of a given throughout this entire thing.

760
00:37:54,150 --> 00:37:55,831
So we basically presented them with two options.

761
00:37:55,872 --> 00:37:58,734
So one, we could go through and manually restore your data.

762
00:37:59,194 --> 00:38:01,556
As I mentioned before, this is a pretty trying proposition.

763
00:38:01,596 --> 00:38:03,157
It's kind of like looking for a needle in a haystack.

764
00:38:04,018 --> 00:38:10,102
We could get clues from players like their account name, the last few things that they did, the state of their collection.

765
00:38:10,682 --> 00:38:13,865
There's a number of clues that we could maybe triangulate and try and figure out who it was,

766
00:38:13,905 --> 00:38:17,447
but we didn't want to give someone access to someone else's account in case they came and asked for it later.

767
00:38:17,467 --> 00:38:19,168
So it was kind of a tricky proposition.

768
00:38:19,589 --> 00:38:24,112
We also encountered a strange phenomenon where we'd find someone we're 100% confident this is that person,

769
00:38:24,372 --> 00:38:29,996
and they'd say, oh actually, I'm pretty sure I had two or three gold characters that just don't happen to be part of my collection.

770
00:38:30,617 --> 00:38:33,582
Which is really strange, we have no idea why that would be the case given everything else

771
00:38:33,602 --> 00:38:33,802
as well.

772
00:38:33,842 --> 00:38:35,485
Never the common characters, only the rare characters.

773
00:38:36,545 --> 00:38:38,066
So I'll talk a little later about how we handled that.

774
00:38:38,126 --> 00:38:40,788
But needless to say, this is a very time-consuming exercise.

775
00:38:41,388 --> 00:38:44,630
So we presented an alternative option, which is basically a free starting over gift.

776
00:38:44,730 --> 00:38:47,892
Why would you want your old data when you can get even better new data?

777
00:38:48,772 --> 00:38:54,476
So basically, for 72 hours after we came back up, we basically had this bundle waiting for

778
00:38:54,516 --> 00:38:57,557
people in their mailbox after they finished the tutorial, which would be any new players

779
00:38:57,677 --> 00:38:59,278
or anybody who lost their data before.

780
00:38:59,839 --> 00:39:02,440
And basically the idea was a lot of these players have been playing for a month and

781
00:39:02,480 --> 00:39:02,740
change.

782
00:39:05,182 --> 00:39:08,023
worth about $400 in in-game contents.

783
00:39:09,043 --> 00:39:11,684
That was way more valuable than most people's progression

784
00:39:11,724 --> 00:39:13,465
up until that point, unless they were super hardcore.

785
00:39:13,865 --> 00:39:14,885
Because we knew we couldn't go through

786
00:39:14,905 --> 00:39:16,526
and handle 200,000 users worth of data.

787
00:39:16,786 --> 00:39:18,166
Hopefully a bunch of people would just go through

788
00:39:18,186 --> 00:39:18,907
and take it and run.

789
00:39:19,607 --> 00:39:21,167
The idea here is that we were comfortable

790
00:39:21,228 --> 00:39:23,748
sacrificing revenue for retention.

791
00:39:23,808 --> 00:39:25,869
We wanted to make sure that at least players

792
00:39:25,889 --> 00:39:26,990
would stick around and maybe one day

793
00:39:27,010 --> 00:39:28,810
they'll trust us enough again to spend money in our game.

794
00:39:30,041 --> 00:39:32,283
So during this period, right after I made that post,

795
00:39:32,323 --> 00:39:35,547
we almost overnight, we had over 2,000 requests that came in.

796
00:39:36,188 --> 00:39:39,051
Normally we have one person that does customer service part time,

797
00:39:39,772 --> 00:39:42,775
but this go around, everybody stopped what they were doing in the company,

798
00:39:42,795 --> 00:39:45,979
across multiple projects, disciplines, everybody was doing customer service.

799
00:39:45,999 --> 00:39:47,721
You're an artist, an engineer, producer, it doesn't matter.

800
00:39:47,741 --> 00:39:50,304
You're either in Freshdesk talking to high-rate customers.

801
00:39:51,145 --> 00:39:53,366
or you were going through and trying to find their data in the database.

802
00:39:54,127 --> 00:39:57,929
And in a strange way, this was actually like a great bonding experience for us as a group.

803
00:39:57,989 --> 00:40:02,153
Obviously, we just suffered this shared trauma, which brought us together in a strange way.

804
00:40:02,793 --> 00:40:05,935
But for the first time, you know, we're an ambitious studio working on multiple things.

805
00:40:06,195 --> 00:40:10,357
this was actually the first time that literally every single person at the studio was doing the exact same thing.

806
00:40:10,897 --> 00:40:12,957
Being able to go through and see customers that were very upset,

807
00:40:13,217 --> 00:40:16,038
and then hopefully by the end of the process, ultimately be satisfied.

808
00:40:16,798 --> 00:40:20,619
When it was all said and done, we manually resolved over 3,500 requests from people,

809
00:40:21,099 --> 00:40:25,161
which is good, that means a lot of people took the free bundle instead of going through and reaching out to us.

810
00:40:25,961 --> 00:40:30,482
But ultimately, even though we tried to front-load it, it took us months to fully work through all of these requests.

811
00:40:31,535 --> 00:40:34,797
So despite all of this stuff, there were still people who weren't happy.

812
00:40:35,277 --> 00:40:36,598
You can't please everyone.

813
00:40:37,538 --> 00:40:41,360
So lots of colorful comments on the forums and in mails and in reviews and whatnot.

814
00:40:42,441 --> 00:40:43,981
And frankly, they had every right to be upset.

815
00:40:44,402 --> 00:40:47,823
We kind of broke the fundamental covenant of we will take care of your data.

816
00:40:48,524 --> 00:40:52,345
So while we were doing everything in our power to try and help folks, you can't make everybody

817
00:40:52,385 --> 00:40:52,646
happy.

818
00:40:53,286 --> 00:40:56,367
Thankfully, there were a lot of people that saw things another way.

819
00:40:56,908 --> 00:40:58,508
The way we were handling it, the way that we were...

820
00:40:58,900 --> 00:41:02,184
doing kind of one-on-one support for every single person, that we were very communicative.

821
00:41:02,504 --> 00:41:06,168
People seemed to be very appreciative of that approach, and frankly, we had a very strong

822
00:41:06,208 --> 00:41:09,271
relationship with our community beforehand, which I think helped set the table to make

823
00:41:09,311 --> 00:41:13,015
sure that we would get the benefit of the doubt when some of this stuff ultimately happened.

824
00:41:14,216 --> 00:41:15,437
So in terms of consequences...

825
00:41:16,014 --> 00:41:18,256
As I mentioned before, all of our KPIs dropped to nothing.

826
00:41:18,716 --> 00:41:21,098
We had no idea what to expect when the game went live again.

827
00:41:21,479 --> 00:41:25,242
We were presuming that our revenue was going to go through and take a big hit.

828
00:41:25,282 --> 00:41:28,164
Maybe some people would eventually go through and come back, but again, we didn't really

829
00:41:28,184 --> 00:41:28,945
know what to expect.

830
00:41:29,566 --> 00:41:35,371
Thankfully, when we relaunched, everything bounced back a lot better than we expected.

831
00:41:35,451 --> 00:41:39,214
So we took a little bit of a hit, but when we did our next content update at the end

832
00:41:39,234 --> 00:41:39,535
of the month...

833
00:41:40,420 --> 00:41:43,121
Our numbers spiked again, like they always do with the content update, and we were able

834
00:41:43,161 --> 00:41:46,122
to more or less, obviously we still had a lot of work to do behind the scenes to make

835
00:41:46,142 --> 00:41:48,643
sure everyone was satisfied, but we were able to keep sailing.

836
00:41:48,663 --> 00:41:49,343
It didn't sink us.

837
00:41:50,183 --> 00:41:54,264
In addition, we migrated over from the back-end partner that will not be named to Mission,

838
00:41:54,304 --> 00:41:56,225
who is an amazing back-end partner that we've been working with now.

839
00:41:56,305 --> 00:41:58,246
I highly recommend it if you're looking for a game as a service.

840
00:41:58,286 --> 00:41:59,146
They never delete your data.

841
00:42:00,666 --> 00:42:06,328
So if you ever find yourself in a similar situation, I hope to God that you don't, here

842
00:42:06,348 --> 00:42:07,588
are some general takeaways.

843
00:42:08,908 --> 00:42:11,350
that you can bear in mind if and when that happens.

844
00:42:12,090 --> 00:42:14,952
So first and foremost is obviously taking responsibility.

845
00:42:15,973 --> 00:42:19,835
I did not mention the name of the other company that we worked with because ultimately it

846
00:42:19,855 --> 00:42:21,196
was our responsibility to deal with this.

847
00:42:21,216 --> 00:42:22,697
It was our responsibility to test their work.

848
00:42:23,404 --> 00:42:26,846
Our customers don't care who ultimately did the actual action.

849
00:42:26,906 --> 00:42:30,949
It's on us as developers to maintain the sanctity of our environment and their data and everything

850
00:42:30,969 --> 00:42:31,469
else as well.

851
00:42:32,250 --> 00:42:34,511
But it's also important to make sure that you keep your chin up.

852
00:42:35,452 --> 00:42:39,194
Obviously, if you ever find yourself in a situation remotely close to this, it can be

853
00:42:39,214 --> 00:42:39,955
pretty dark times.

854
00:42:40,075 --> 00:42:44,938
It's easy to succumb to despair, to feel like you're a terrible person or a terrible game

855
00:42:44,958 --> 00:42:48,460
developer, and really, at the end of the day, shit happens.

856
00:42:49,181 --> 00:42:51,422
You're not going to be able to move forward if you're dwelling in the past.

857
00:42:51,875 --> 00:42:55,927
So, you know, just try and be open and authentic and genuine with your fans and

858
00:42:56,148 --> 00:42:58,415
hopefully they'll give you another shot at it moving forward.

859
00:42:59,994 --> 00:43:04,535
I mentioned before that people would make some pretty strange requests of us that really

860
00:43:04,555 --> 00:43:05,796
had no foundation in fact.

861
00:43:06,536 --> 00:43:10,597
However, when push came to shove, people asked for those gold characters, we just gave it

862
00:43:10,617 --> 00:43:10,817
to them.

863
00:43:12,137 --> 00:43:13,197
This was for a number of reasons.

864
00:43:13,317 --> 00:43:15,158
One, it was the fastest way to deal with the situation.

865
00:43:15,218 --> 00:43:18,959
As I mentioned, we had thousands of requests that were coming in, and the longer it took

866
00:43:18,979 --> 00:43:22,319
for us to go through and respond to one user and satisfy their needs, there were dozens

867
00:43:22,339 --> 00:43:24,020
of other users that were still waiting for a response.

868
00:43:24,060 --> 00:43:25,120
We needed to move through it quickly.

869
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:29,101
It was also because we trusted them, even if we didn't always trust them.

870
00:43:30,004 --> 00:43:32,151
But they deserved it in part because we owed it to them.

871
00:43:32,211 --> 00:43:33,355
We're the ones that have made the mistake.

872
00:43:33,817 --> 00:43:35,162
We need to give them the benefit of the doubt.

873
00:43:35,559 --> 00:43:37,460
And frankly, anything we do to go through and make them happy,

874
00:43:37,820 --> 00:43:38,781
the better off we'll ultimately be.

875
00:43:39,061 --> 00:43:43,123
A lot of this aligns with some of the exploitable customer service policies

876
00:43:43,223 --> 00:43:46,285
with companies like Costco and Nordstrom, famously,

877
00:43:46,765 --> 00:43:48,626
that we try to go through and adopt as well as part of this.

878
00:43:49,647 --> 00:43:52,028
And even if you just look at it from a purely pragmatic perspective,

879
00:43:52,829 --> 00:43:55,470
while it may seem like players are exploiting you for free stuff,

880
00:43:55,790 --> 00:43:59,152
another way to look at it is this is a very low-cost investment

881
00:43:59,272 --> 00:44:00,933
in retention of our highest-value users.

882
00:44:01,053 --> 00:44:02,874
If they're going to be happy and they're going to go through and stick around,

883
00:44:03,257 --> 00:44:07,220
Giving them a few free things that they clearly covet early on really isn't going to move

884
00:44:07,240 --> 00:44:08,341
the needle that much in the long term.

885
00:44:08,361 --> 00:44:11,204
It's much more valuable to have these people stick around for the long haul.

886
00:44:12,125 --> 00:44:14,187
I mentioned that we have a really strong relationship with our community.

887
00:44:14,827 --> 00:44:18,871
My in-game handle is MightyZug, and whenever I start typing Discord, someone invariably

888
00:44:18,911 --> 00:44:19,572
posts this image.

889
00:44:20,592 --> 00:44:24,276
We're always doing little AMAs and whatnot with our fans and the forums.

890
00:44:24,716 --> 00:44:26,298
on Discord, in our in-game chat.

891
00:44:26,878 --> 00:44:29,080
And so we're also, we all actively play the game.

892
00:44:29,380 --> 00:44:31,202
We don't play the game with like God-level accounts.

893
00:44:31,282 --> 00:44:33,163
Some of us are high-level, some of us are mid-level.

894
00:44:33,844 --> 00:44:36,927
But as a result, people see us in prizefights and other in-game events.

895
00:44:37,347 --> 00:44:40,770
And as a result, you know, the community really knows who we are as people.

896
00:44:40,830 --> 00:44:43,392
They see us as accessible and relatable,

897
00:44:43,733 --> 00:44:46,435
as opposed to just representatives of a faceless entity,

898
00:44:46,955 --> 00:44:47,796
which I think really helped.

899
00:44:48,277 --> 00:44:50,859
We're also very transparent about our gameplay and business decisions.

900
00:44:50,879 --> 00:44:52,560
Whenever we need to go through and make changes, we always...

901
00:44:52,880 --> 00:44:54,841
post our rationale on the forum if we need to go through

902
00:44:54,861 --> 00:44:56,762
and change the way we're distributing content

903
00:44:56,902 --> 00:44:58,604
in order to increase revenue

904
00:44:58,644 --> 00:44:59,724
so we can reinvest it in the game.

905
00:44:59,764 --> 00:45:00,965
We tell them, hey, we're doing this

906
00:45:00,985 --> 00:45:02,947
so we can increase revenue so we can reinvest it in the game.

907
00:45:03,467 --> 00:45:06,049
And generally, our fans are very receptive to that.

908
00:45:06,689 --> 00:45:08,370
We also respond to every single user review

909
00:45:08,410 --> 00:45:09,251
that we get, good or bad.

910
00:45:09,591 --> 00:45:10,992
It's important to remember that your community

911
00:45:11,052 --> 00:45:12,613
is not just your most hardcore players

912
00:45:12,653 --> 00:45:13,554
that are in your Discord.

913
00:45:13,794 --> 00:45:15,455
They're anyone who's ultimately reaching out to you

914
00:45:15,515 --> 00:45:18,037
and your review board is a public-facing forum

915
00:45:18,057 --> 00:45:19,538
where people can see who you are

916
00:45:19,558 --> 00:45:20,718
and how you engage with your fans.

917
00:45:21,719 --> 00:45:22,340
Last but not least.

918
00:45:23,160 --> 00:45:28,002
Being open, honest and empathetic beyond just regular updates with folks, as I mentioned

919
00:45:28,022 --> 00:45:33,124
before, when you have people reaching out to you with extremely irate, profanity laden

920
00:45:33,764 --> 00:45:37,186
emails, it's important to remember that empathy begets empathy.

921
00:45:37,686 --> 00:45:40,588
This is an example of some of the language that we would go through news when talking

922
00:45:40,608 --> 00:45:41,008
with folks.

923
00:45:41,268 --> 00:45:42,508
We understand that you're upset.

924
00:45:42,568 --> 00:45:46,350
We would be too, putting ourselves in their shoes and showing that we're real people on

925
00:45:46,390 --> 00:45:46,770
the other end.

926
00:45:47,659 --> 00:45:51,900
And you'd be surprised at how many people that started with just completely dark, utter

927
00:45:52,060 --> 00:45:56,281
vitriol by the time the entire process was over, they were apologizing for their past

928
00:45:56,321 --> 00:45:59,281
behavior in the first email, even though they had every right to be upset.

929
00:46:00,202 --> 00:46:03,782
Obviously, building your faction with your community in advance really goes a long way

930
00:46:04,042 --> 00:46:07,063
before the crisis occurs to make sure that you can ultimately weather the storm.

931
00:46:08,023 --> 00:46:11,464
So in conclusion, if you ever want to bring your team together and galvanize the support

932
00:46:11,484 --> 00:46:13,064
of your player base, simply delete everybody's data.

933
00:46:13,084 --> 00:46:13,724
It works every time.

934
00:46:13,744 --> 00:46:15,004
Thank you.

935
00:46:15,124 --> 00:46:16,185
Thank you.

936
00:46:25,540 --> 00:46:28,022
Cool, so I think this is the time where I remind everyone

937
00:46:28,182 --> 00:46:30,083
to go through and make sure that you fill out your surveys.

938
00:46:30,183 --> 00:46:34,545
But I guess we're going to do Q&A. So either we'll

939
00:46:34,585 --> 00:46:35,206
all come up here.

